"NOT FOUND"|"Wodan, Wodan sane, quem adieeta littera Gwodan dixerunt, ipse est, qui apud Romanos Mercurius dicitur, et ab universis gentibus ut deus adoratur. Paulus Diae. qu. by Orelli. Schweizer-Sidler suggests that the similarity of the two names Teutates and Vodamus may have facilitated the identification of Wodan and Mercury. Mars (another German divinity acc. to Tacitus) is identified with Tyr or Ziu and among some German tribes with Er. Ziu is probably Dyaus the Greek Zeus, and therefore Caesar may be thinking of this God when he says that they worshipped the Sun. Tacitus also says that they worshipped Hercules, and that some of the Suebi even acknowledged the divinity of Isis."

